  "prompt": "If we evolved from apes then why are there still apes around today?",
  "response": "The idea that humans evolved from apes is a common misunderstanding of evolutionary theory. In reality, humans and modern apes share a common ancestor that lived millions of years ago. This common ancestor was neither human nor any of the modern ape species we see today. Over time, different species evolved from this common ancestor, leading to the variety of primates we have now, including humans, chimpanzees, gorillas, and orangutans.\n\nEvolution does not progress in a linear fashion where one species simply turns into another; rather, it\u2019s a branching process. While some populations may evolve into new species, others may remain relatively unchanged and continue to coexist. This is why we still have apes today: they have adapted to their environments through their own evolutionary paths, just as humans have adapted to theirs. Thus, both humans and apes are currently existing species that have their own distinct evolutionary histories.",
